4 A BILL FOR AN ACT ENTITLED: “AN ACT REVISING EDUCATIONAL LAWS TO PROVIDE FUNDING FOR
5 CAREER AND TECHNICAL EDUCATION IN THE MIDDLE GRADES; REQUIRING THE SUPERINTENDENT
6 OF PUBLIC INSTRUCTION TO ADOPT RULES FOR THE DISTRIBUTION OF THE FUNDS; PROVIDING
7 RULEMAKING AUTHORITY; AND PROVIDING AN APPROPRIATION.”
8
9 WHEREAS, the academic requirements for junior high schools, middle schools, and 7th and 8th grade
10 programs contained in the accreditation standards of the Board of Public Education include "career and
11 technical education courses or pathways such as agriculture, business education, family and consumer
12 sciences, health occupations and industrial technology education"; and
13 WHEREAS, high schools receive additional state funding that recognizes the unique costs of
14 maintaining high-quality career and technical education pathways; and
15 WHEREAS, there is an increasing awareness of the importance of providing high-quality career and
16 technical education, including career exposure and exploration, to students in the middle grades; and
17 WHEREAS, the Office of Public Instruction has utilized the increased flexibility under Perkins V and
18 Montana's Perkins Plan to provide modest $5,000 Perkins Secondary Reserve Grants limited to small schools
19 on a first-come, first-served basis; and
20 WHEREAS, a long-overdue state investment to support middle grades career and technical education
21 could enhance the Perkins Secondary Reserve Grants and allow larger schools to participate as well.
22
23 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF MONTANA:
24
25 NEW SECTION. Section 1. Funding for career and technical education programs in middle
26 grades. (1) The superintendent of public instruction shall annually distribute money from the appropriation for
27 middle grades career and technical education. The money must be allocated to elementary and K-12 school
28 districts with accredited and approved junior high, middle school, or 7th and 8th grade programs.
